---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Knowledge OS Proof"
  description="A case-study style view of Knowledge OS: a human-reviewed operating system that turns signals, source material, and agent work into useful artifacts."
  image="/knowledge-os/system-map.png"
>
  <div class="container-wide">
    <section class="workbench-hero">
      <div class="panel workbench-hero-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Knowledge OS proof page</p>
        <h1>A human-reviewed operating system for turning signals into useful artifacts.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          Knowledge OS is the internal operating layer behind my current work. It keeps source material, agent runs, review queues, and publishing artifacts visible enough to trust and improve.
        </p>
        <div class="pill-row">
          <span class="pill blue">Signal intake</span>
          <span class="pill sage">Promotion gates</span>
          <span class="pill plum">Human review</span>
          <span class="pill copper">Artifact loops</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <aside class="panel workbench-card">
        <div class="sticky-note">
          <span class="pill sage">Operating idea</span>
          <strong>Raw material is not trusted memory.</strong>
          <p>Signals enter as leads. Review gates decide what becomes reusable. Workflows produce artifacts. Feedback tunes the next cycle.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-dark">
          <div class="diagram-node"><div class="eyebrow">Capture</div><strong>Signals</strong></div>
          <div class="diagram-arrow">-&gt;</div>
          <div class="diagram-node"><div class="eyebrow">Govern</div><strong>Promote</strong></div>
          <div class="diagram-arrow">-&gt;</div>
          <div class="diagram-node"><div class="eyebrow">Use</div><strong>Artifacts</strong></div>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>The Problem</h2>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill copper">Context sprawl</span>
          <h3>Useful signals arrive everywhere</h3>
          <p>X posts, newsletters, articles, agent sessions, notes, and conversation fragments all carry useful information, but most of it should not immediately become trusted knowledge.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill plum">Judgment bottleneck</span>
          <h3>Review is the scarce layer</h3>
          <p>The hard part is deciding what matters, what should be ignored, what needs a source check, and what deserves to become an artifact or memory.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>The System Map</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        The current Knowledge OS separates intake, durable memory, governed process, and reviewable output. It is deliberately inspectable: every useful loop leaves an artifact.
      </p>
      <figure class="image-frame">
        <img src="/knowledge-os/system-map.png" alt="Knowledge OS system map showing intake, knowledge core, artifacts, and feedback loop." loading="lazy" />
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>How It Proves the Services Method</h2>
      <div class="process-roadmap">
        <article class="panel process-step agent" data-step="01">
          <div class="eyebrow">Discover</div>
          <h3>Capture the real flow</h3>
          <p>Knowledge OS starts from actual source material and work traces instead of theoretical use cases.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel process-step guardrail" data-step="02">
          <div class="eyebrow">Advise</div>
          <h3>Decide what deserves trust</h3>
          <p>Promotion gates separate raw signals from reusable memory, reducing the risk of treating every fragment as equally valid.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="panel process-step review" data-step="03">
          <div class="eyebrow">Build</div>
          <h3>Ship reviewable artifacts</h3>
          <p>The system produces briefs, queues, notes, drafts, and run records that can be inspected, improved, or discarded.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Current Live Lanes</h2>
      <div class="proof-strip">
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill blue">X Scout</span>
          <strong>Engagement Radar</strong>
          <p>Tracks relevant public signals, produces candidate queues, and keeps reply work behind explicit review.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill sage">Newsletter intake</span>
          <strong>Source queue</strong>
          <p>Turns email/newsletter material into reviewable leads without treating raw email as canonical knowledge.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill plum">Knowledge Desk</span>
          <strong>Human cockpit</strong>
          <p>Shows the current state of signals, review queues, and next useful actions in plain files.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <div class="callout">
        <p class="eyebrow">Why this matters commercially</p>
        <h2>The same pattern applies to business operations.</h2>
        <p>
          Most teams do not need "more AI" first. They need a better operating loop: intake, triage, review, execution, feedback, and memory. Knowledge OS is my proof that I build those loops for my own work before recommending them to anyone else.
        </p>
        <p><a href="/workshops/">See the services process &rarr;</a></p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
